**In Functions (Methods)**

When `static` is used in front of a function (method) declaration, it means that the function can be called without creating an instance of the class. The function is not bound to any instance of the class, and it shares the same state across all instances of the class.

Example (Java):
```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void myFunction() {
        // code here
    }
}
```
You can call `myFunction()` without creating an instance of `MyClass`:
```java
MyClass.myFunction();
```
**In Variables**

When `static` is used in front of a variable declaration, it means that the variable is shared across all instances of the class. It's essentially a global variable within the class.

Example (Java):
```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myVariable = 10;
}
```
You can access `myVariable` without creating an instance of `MyClass`:
```java
System.out.println(MyClass.myVariable); // prints 10
